70
00:04:22,762 --> 00:04:25,560
Not even Phillip,
because it doesn't need software.

71
00:04:26,299 --> 00:04:29,132
- Is she asleep?
- No, and she needs a bath.

72
00:04:29,536 --> 00:04:32,903
- She'll wind up in the closet if I do it.
- That's fine.

73
00:04:33,806 --> 00:04:36,639
You know, even if Robert's okay with it,
and he won't be.

74
00:04:36,743 --> 00:04:41,146
- I don't understand what that thing will do.
- We'll let them go at it for two months.

75
00:04:41,247 --> 00:04:43,943
- They do theirs, we do ours.
- They said it'd take 14 hours.

76
00:04:44,050 --> 00:04:46,143
Don't eat that. Seriously, it's bad.

77
00:04:46,252 --> 00:04:48,720
We threw the first couple of batches out.
The filter.

78
00:04:48,821 --> 00:04:50,516
What about crushed?

79
00:04:51,925 --> 00:04:53,449
These guys are funded.

80
00:04:53,726 --> 00:04:56,889
- These guys are... What?
- Liquid helium. These guys are funded.

81
00:04:56,996 --> 00:04:58,623
That's what this is.

82
00:04:58,731 --> 00:05:01,063
That's the whole difference.
That's what the box is.

83
00:05:01,167 --> 00:05:04,295
We don't have to play the game
where we're going back and forth...

84
00:05:04,404 --> 00:05:08,340
coming up with innovative ways to make it
colder and unusable in the process.

85
00:05:08,441 --> 00:05:11,604
- Aaron, I need the hexagonal set.
- This is unmarketable.

86
00:05:11,711 --> 00:05:14,407
By coming at it from the back end,
rather than changing...

87
00:05:14,514 --> 00:05:17,677
the surrounding temperature,
we'll change the level it'll conduct...

88
00:05:17,784 --> 00:05:20,617
the transition temperature.
And by bombarding these edges...

89
00:05:20,720 --> 00:05:23,917
They're dropping the ceramic,
the temperature lower and lower.

90
00:05:24,023 --> 00:05:27,823
It makes the ceramic less resistant
and knocks out the interior magnetic field.

91
00:05:27,927 --> 00:05:30,657
What I'm saying is
we drop the box down on it.

92
00:05:31,231 --> 00:05:34,564
Focus our own magnetic field to negate,
knock out with the inverse...

93
00:05:34,667 --> 00:05:36,532
what's going on inside the ceramic.

94
00:05:36,636 --> 00:05:40,663
That should change the transition
temperature to something we can work with.

95
00:05:40,773 --> 00:05:44,209
- What are we saying that is?
- Hopefully, near room temperature.

96
00:05:45,478 --> 00:05:48,174
What is that about?
The best mathematician is a lazy one?

97
00:05:48,281 --> 00:05:51,011
- What did you ask for?
- I asked. I need the hexagonal set.

98
00:05:51,117 --> 00:05:52,778
- What did you call it?
- Just come on.

99
00:05:52,885 --> 00:05:54,648
- Are these Type One?
- The superconductors?

100
00:05:54,754 --> 00:05:56,415
Yeah, they're Type One.

101
00:05:56,522 --> 00:05:58,149
Is that going to be a problem?

102
00:05:58,258 --> 00:06:01,125
There's plenty lying around at work,
but they're all bar coded.

103
00:06:01,227 --> 00:06:04,822
- If I have to, I'll buy the kits.
- What are you doing about the source?

104
00:06:04,931 --> 00:06:06,262
What?

105
00:06:06,966 --> 00:06:09,901
- I can get them.
- You can... Are you sure?

106
00:06:10,003 --> 00:06:11,800
I thought you didn't like this idea.

107
00:06:11,904 --> 00:06:14,873
Buy them if you have to.
Everything else we can take care of.

108
00:06:14,974 --> 00:06:16,339
What about the source here?

109
00:06:16,442 --> 00:06:18,967
You know that story
about how NASA spent millions...

110
00:06:19,078 --> 00:06:22,878
developing this pen that writes in zero-G?
Did you ever read that?

111
00:06:22,982 --> 00:06:26,418
- And how Russia solved the problem?
- Yeah, they used a pencil.

112
00:06:26,719 --> 00:06:28,619
Right, a normal wooden pencil.

113
00:06:29,489 --> 00:06:32,617
It just seems like Phillip takes
the NASA route almost every time.

114
00:06:32,725 --> 00:06:35,387
- Palladium?
- You've got their diagram, what does it say?

115
00:06:35,495 --> 00:06:37,429
They use a ratio of platinum and palladium.

116
00:06:37,530 --> 00:06:39,498
That's not necessary
with the changes I made.

117
00:06:39,599 --> 00:06:41,863
They're just showing off.
If you have it, use it.

118
00:06:41,968 --> 00:06:43,435
I want to get a replacement router.

119
00:06:43,536 --> 00:06:46,630
- I'm putting down four ounces of palladium.
- Did Robert look at it?

120
00:06:46,739 --> 00:06:48,502
- I already got his.
- I can't fix it.

121
00:06:48,608 --> 00:06:52,271
- Okay. Where are you getting it?
- Wal-Mart. It's $50.

122
00:06:52,612 --> 00:06:55,274
- Okay. Can you get a receipt, please?
- Yeah.

123
00:06:55,381 --> 00:06:57,611
Wait, platinum or palladium
is less resistant?

124
00:06:57,717 --> 00:06:59,776
- Abe? It's not a...
- Yeah, I don't care.

125
00:06:59,886 --> 00:07:02,377
- So resistance doesn't matter.
- I need an aye or a yes.

126
00:07:02,488 --> 00:07:04,513
- Did you jiggle the...
- The collet nut?

127
00:07:04,624 --> 00:07:07,354
- Robert did it.
- Well, yes. I guess.

128
00:07:07,894 --> 00:07:11,295
- Well, then, which is cheaper?
- You're not going to buy it, are you?

129
00:07:11,397 --> 00:07:14,764
Well, unless you've got
a few grams of palladium lying around.

130
00:07:15,301 --> 00:07:18,031
Why would they put it in there
if you didn't need it?

131
00:07:18,137 --> 00:07:20,196
One catalytic converter. It's fine.

132
00:07:20,306 --> 00:07:22,968
Remember to put it back.
Your emission just went up 300%.

133
00:07:23,076 --> 00:07:24,976
- Is there enough in here?
- Yeah, should be.

134
00:07:25,078 --> 00:07:28,946
If not, we'll pull the one out of my truck.
Okay, copper tubing.

135
00:07:36,456 --> 00:07:39,721
- This will be out of commission, right?
- Without the tubing?

136
00:07:40,660 --> 00:07:43,891
- We can use the Freon, too.
- No, it's going to be room temperature.

137
00:07:43,996 --> 00:07:45,054
I know, just in case.

138
00:07:45,164 --> 00:07:49,191
No, wait. Stop. I'll just buy the tubing.
This isn't saving us money.

139
00:07:55,108 --> 00:07:58,168
- Jay? Hey, man. How are you?
- Good.

140
00:08:19,832 --> 00:08:21,993
Should we be wearing goggles?

141
00:08:24,370 --> 00:08:26,565
- Should we be wearing goggles?
- What?

142
00:08:26,672 --> 00:08:28,936
Goggles. Should we be wearing goggles?

143
00:08:36,249 --> 00:08:38,683
Wait. Phillip, you don't want
to come out here.

144
00:08:38,785 --> 00:08:40,980
Phillip, grab a mask, okay?

145
00:09:21,828 --> 00:09:24,296
It is, though, right? It's not just me?

146
00:09:24,397 --> 00:09:27,780
No, it's definitely smaller,
but it just seems that way.

147
00:09:27,806 --> 00:09:29,452
Take what they have.

148
00:09:29,735 --> 00:09:32,169
